******
[1] New York
Date: Tue 23 Sep 2014
Source: Irondequoit Post [edited]
http://www.irondequoitpost.com/article/20140923/NEWS/140929861


The Wayne County Public Health Department has received notification from the NYS Department of Health (NYSDOH) that a 4th horse has tested positive for EEE (eastern equine encephalitis). This horse was located in the town of Galen. The NYSDOH is planning to conduct testing of mosquito pools in this area.

In response to NYS Department of Health Acting Commissioner Dr Zucker making a declaration of an Imminent Threat to Public Health for mosquito-borne disease, the Wayne County Board of Supervisors has authorized aerial spraying for mosquitoes in the affected areas. In accordance with the New York State regulations and the New York State Mosquito-borne Illness Surveillance & Response Plan, spraying is part of an effective surveillance and control system. Aerial spraying is a control measure to diminish mosquito populations which will help to reduce the risk of human infection from the EEE virus.

Wayne County Public Health Director Diane Devlin emphasizes that people in Wayne County need to continue to use personal protective measures to avoid being bitten by mosquitoes. The County will conduct aerial spraying on the evening of Thu 25 Sep 2014 from 6 p.m. till dark.

The product Masterline Kontrol 30-30, which contains permethrin, will be applied in a diluted form. The County has contracted with Duflo Spray-Chemical to conduct the aerial spraying. The procedure is approved by the State Health Department and the Department of Environmental Conservation.

The area to be sprayed has been decreased from 7600 acres [3075 ha] to 1325 acres [536 ha], which includes mostly swampland and wooded areas. [A map of the area showing the boundary areas to be sprayed may be found at the source URL above]. Residents living within the aerial spraying boundaries will be notified 24 hours prior to spraying by the Public Health Department. People in the target area should stay indoors and keep windows and doors closed for 1 hour after spraying. They are also advised to:
- keep pets indoors;
- close the vents on window air conditioners so that outside air doesn't enter the home for 1 hour;
- remove outdoor toys, outdoor furniture, and clothing from the clothesline. Items left outdoors should be washed thoroughly with soap and water before using;
- if you are driving through an area while spraying takes place, close your car windows and vents;
- cover gardens, or rinse homegrown fruits and vegetables thoroughly before cooking or eating.

A copy of the pesticide label and MSDS including all warnings and fact sheets about permethrin aerial spraying can be found on the Wayne County website at http://www.co.wayne.ny.us or obtained by calling the Wayne County Health Department weekdays between 8:30 a.m. to 4 p.m.

For more information on pesticide regulation, contact the New York State Department of Environmental Conservation, Bureau of Pest Management, 625 Broadway, Albany, NY 12233.

For information on EEE, visit http://bit.ly/1pbVEzK

