[The state of Ohio can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2806347,237. Ashtabula and Trumbull counties in north eastern Ohio can be seen on the map at http://geology.com/county-map/ohio-county-map.gif.

These are 2 different states and 2 very different responses to the same situation. While spraying to control mosquitoes is never wrong, it is just a sad commentary that they appear to allow the horse to be a sentinel animal. Most areas use a few chickens as sentinel animals, and are more proactive about their spraying. Furthermore, it seems there should be some encouragement for horse owners to vaccinate their horses, to spray them with horse-approved mosquito and fly control sprays. While NY has had a substantial amount of rain this spring and summer (2014), it still seems it would have been appropriate to advice horse owners to vaccinate and for humans to protect themselves with mosquito repellent.

Then there is the OH response that combines vaccination, and spraying, as well as eliminating water where mosquitoes breed.

Either approach should be effective for controlling mosquitoes, but with vaccination animals have a better chance of survival. Vaccination must be done properly and timely. - Mod.TG]
